Question 1 (16 points)

Your professor has entered into a contract with a biotech company to study a secret gene and puts you on the project. The company will not reveal the identity of the gene or even the source organism.

Being the curious scientist that you are, you decide to ignore the consequences (lawsuits) and to sequence it. The sequence is available in the file “Mystery1.fa”

You hypothesize that the sequence has come from a model organism.

a. Did the gene come from Arabidopsis, C. elegans, Drosophila or some other organism? If you think it came from some other organism is that organism likely a plant or animal? Explain the reasoning behind your conclusion.

BLAST example. Smith-Waterman would have been OK also

#format database (not necessary for full credit)
xdformat -p ~/Day2/Data/Sequences/Proteome/A.thaliana.fa 
xdformat -p ~/Day2/Data/Sequences/Proteome/C.elegans.fa 
xdformat -p ~/Day2/Data/Sequences/Proteome/D.melanogaster.fa 

#run blast
blastp ~/Day2/Data/Sequences/Proteome/A.thaliana.fa Mystery1.fa > A.thaliana_Mystery.blast.out
blastp ~/Day2/Data/Sequences/Proteome/C.elegans.fa Mystery1.fa > C.elegans_Mystery.blast.out
blastp ~/Day2/Data/Sequences/Proteome/D.melanogaster.fa Mystery1.fa > D.melanogaster_Mystery.blast.out

The gene most likely came from a plant, but not from Arabidopsis. It had a much stronger hit with Arabidopsis than with the other organisms, suggesting that it is a plant gene. However the percent identity with Arabidopsis was only 80%; I would expect a near-perfect match if this was actually an Arabidospis protein.

1 pt for species
1 pt for binary plant or animal
1 pt code
2 pts explanation

b. List the best protein match for each organism (if there is one). Are these matches significant? How did you decide signficance?

Organsism Best Match P-Value % ID
A. thaliana AT4G08920.1 0 80
C. elegans CE42669 0.56 24
D. Melanogaster FBpp0080934 2.3e-39 28
—————— ————- ——— ——

Based on the p-value and using a cutoff of 0.05, The matches in A. thaliana and D. melanogaster are signficant whereas the C. elegans hit is not.

3 pt 1 for each organism
1 pt significance explanation

c. For each organism do you think there is a single orthlog? Why or why not?

For Arabidopsis there appears to be a single orthlog because the next best match has a much less signficant p-value and a lower percent identity. In Drosophila at first glance it appears that there are four paralogs that match equally well but these turn out to be isoforms of the same protein. Answers for 1 or 4 orthologs in Drosophila accepted as correct. In C. elegans there appear to be no orthologs.

1 single ortholog
1 explanation

d. Which program did you use to answer this question? Why? What advantages and disadvantages does it have over other choices?

I used blastp because it is faster and provides a p-value without needing to create a shuffled sequence. Those reasons also list its advantages. Disadvantages, relative to Smith-Waterman is that it is not guaranteed to return the best possible alignment.

1 pt listing program
1 pt explanation
1 pt advantage
1 pt disadvantage

Question 3 (4 points)

The EMBOSS suite contains a program called preg that lets you search for protein patterns using regular expressions. Suppose you want to find how how often IAN occurs in the worm proteome. You would type

preg -sequence wormpep -pattern "IAN" -outfile out

The pattern below matches C2H2 Zn-finger proteins.

C.{2,4}C.{3}[LIVMFYWC].{8}H.{3,5}H

a. How many fly proteins have this pattern?

ln -s ../Assignment_2/flypep ./
preg -sequence flypep "C.{2,4}C.{3}[LIVMFYWC].{8}H.{3,5}H" -outfile zn.out
more zn.out 
grep -c "Sequence:" zn.out

There are 738 proteins with this pattern

1 pt code
1 pt answer

b. What is the average number of Zn-fingers per protein?

There are a lot of ways to solve this. I count the number of occurences of the pattern “regex:” which occurs with every hit. Once this is done then we can just divide this number by the total number of proteins with a hit

grep -c "regex:" zn.out

The total number of hits is 3334, so the average number is 3334/738 = 4.5 hits per protein.

1 pt code
1 pt answer

(Some people answered this is avergae number of hits across all proteins in the proteome. While that is not what I intended with the question I give fill credit for that answer as well).

Question 4 (6 points)

Perform the same Zn-finger search against the shuffled fly proteome.

a. How many proteins have this pattern, and what is the average number of Zn-fingers per protein?

 shuffleseq flypep flypep.shuffle.fa
 preg -sequence flypep.shuffle.fa "C.{2,4}C.{3}[LIVMFYWC].{8}H.{3,5}H" -outfile zn.shuffle.out
 more zn.shuffle.out 
 grep -c "Sequence:" zn.shuffle.out 
 grep -c "regex:" zn.shuffle.out

17 sequences have the Zn finger pattern and there are a total of 20 hits. So the average number of hits per protein is {r round(20/17,1)}

1 pt shuffle code
1 pt calculation code
1 pt # proteins
1 pt average Zn-fingers

b. Explain why you think the shuffled sequence is similar/different from the real sequence with respect to the C2H2 Zn-finger pattern.

There are many fewer hits and many fewer hits per protein in the shuffled sequence. This indicates that the Zn Finger pattern occurs more often than expected by chance in the real proteome, suggesting that the motif has some function.

2 pt explanation

Question 5 (5 points)

a. Describe three advantages to using a version control system like Git. 3 pt 1 for each advantage

  1. Collaboration. It allows easy collaboration between different researchers.
  2. Reproducibility. By storing code in a repository it enables other researchers to reproduce what has been done.
  3. Documentatinon. By tracking changes we know how the code has evolved.
  4. backup. If I make a change that messes something up it is easy to go back.

b. Describe two things that you can do to make your code more reproducible and understandable. 2 pt 1 for each thing

  1. Good commenting
  2. Logical variable names
  3. Use a version control system.

Question 7 (6 points)

a. What is the mean change in muscle mass in the non-dominant arm for each gender?

tapply(data$NDRM.CH,data$Gender,mean,na.rm=T)
##   Female     Male 
## 62.38897 40.00652

1 pt code
2 pt 1 for each accurate mean

b. Does gender have a significant effect on change in muscle mass in the non-dominant arm? How do you know?

summary(aov(data$NDRM.CH ~ data$Gender))
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## data$Gender   1 107699  107699   114.1 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   883 833705     944                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 187 observations deleted due to missingness
#OR

t.test(data$NDRM.CH ~ data$Gender)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data$NDRM.CH by data$Gender
## t = 11.4935, df = 870.405, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  18.56029 26.20462
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Female   mean in group Male 
##             62.38897             40.00652

Yes, Gender has a highly signiificant effect on the change in muscle mass. This is clear because the p-value for the Gender effect via ANOVA is < 2e -16.

1 pt test for significance
2 pts explanation
